"Bioengineering (biomedical engineering) operates under several overlapping paradigms—conceptual frameworks, methodological approaches, and epistemological shifts—that guide research, design, and translation. These have evolved from reductionist biology/medicine toward integrative, problem-solving, and design-oriented strategies. As of 2026, the field reflects a broader transition in the biomedical sciences.
pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

1. The Engineering Paradigm in Biomedical Sciences (vs. Traditional Physics Paradigm)
A key philosophical and methodological shift, articulated by scholars like Mieke Boon, contrasts the dominant physics paradigm (focused on universal laws, representational knowledge, and fundamental understanding through reductionism, as in classical biochemistry) with an engineering paradigm.
pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov +1

Core of the engineering paradigm: Knowledge functions as an epistemic tool—constructed, modular, and purpose-built for solving real-world problems. It prioritizes utility, context-specific applicability, design, iteration, and intervention over pure representation or discovery of immutable truths.
sciencedirect.com
Implications: Emphasizes modeling/simulation for practical outcomes (e.g., systems biology, synthetic biology), interdisciplinary integration, and "useful knowledge" tailored to clinical or industrial needs. This fits fields like synthetic biology and tissue engineering better than purely descriptive approaches.
tandfonline.com
It enables recognition of aspects neglected in traditional paradigms, such as context-dependence, modularity, and iterative design-build-test cycles.

This paradigm underpins much of modern bioengineering's problem-solving ethos.

2. Tissue Engineering and Regenerative Medicine Paradigm
Tissue engineering (often paired with regenerative medicine) emerged as a transformative paradigm in the late 20th/early 21st century, shifting from replacement (e.g., prosthetics, transplants) to regeneration and restoration.
biotech-asia.org

Core triad: Cells + scaffolds/biomaterials + bioactive signals (growth factors, mechanical cues).
Key features: Use of decellularized matrices, 3D/4D bioprinting, stem cells/organoids, and bioreactors to create functional tissues/organs. It treats the body as a regenerative system amenable to engineering control.
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov
Extensions: On-demand tissue/organ engineering (a grand challenge), hybrid scaffolds (biological + synthetic), and in vivo regeneration. Sub-paradigms include lung bioengineering (acellular/artificial/hybrid scaffolds, lung-on-a-chip) and cardiac muscle engineering as exemplars for broader regenerative approaches.
mdpi.com
This paradigm moves medicine toward restorative rather than palliative or substitutive interventions.

3. Synthetic Biology and Programmable Biology Paradigm
This views biological systems as engineerable "machines" or circuits—redesigning genomes, pathways, cells, and organisms using standardized parts, modularity, and rational design (inspired by electrical/computer engineering).
pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov

Approaches: Genetic code expansion, CRISPR-based editing, engineered cells for therapy (e.g., CAR-T extensions), and microbial factories.
Integration: With tissue engineering for "living" materials and dynamic, responsive constructs.
It enables bottom-up construction of novel functions, contrasting top-down analysis in traditional biology.

4. Convergence and Data-Driven/AI-Augmented Paradigms
Modern bioengineering increasingly relies on multi-scale integration and computational tools:
AI/ML and digital twins: Generative AI for protein design, predictive modeling, personalized physiology avatars (multi-scale digital twins simulating individual physiology).
today.ucsd.edu
Systems and precision paradigms: Network biology, multi-omics, and closed-loop systems (e.g., smart implants, adaptive therapies).
Nanotechnology and biomimetics: Bottom-up assembly at molecular scales, inspired by nature.
Interdisciplinary convergence: Biology + engineering + data science + materials + ethics, creating hybrid fields like neuroengineering, immunoengineering, and biomechatronics.
tmrjournals.com

5. Grand Challenges as Orienting Frameworks
Expert consensus (e.g., 2024 IEEE EMBS task force) frames current research around five interconnected grand challenges that act as pragmatic paradigms for high-impact work:
today.ucsd.edu

Personalized physiology avatars (precision engineering + precision medicine).
On-demand tissue and organ engineering.
AI-driven brain-interface systems and neuroscience.
Engineering the immune system.
Engineering genomes, cells, and related systems.

These emphasize translation, scalability, equity, and ethical integration.

Overarching Characteristics and Shifts
From reactive to proactive/preventive: Toward predictive, personalized, and programmable interventions.
Methodological: Design-build-test-learn cycles, advanced manufacturing (bioprinting), human-relevant models (organoids over animal models in some contexts), and living systematic reviews.
Epistemic: Knowledge as tools for intervention; strong focus on clinical translation, regulatory science, and real-world problem-solving.
tmrjournals.com
Challenges: Scalability, vascularization/innervation, immunogenicity, ethics (e.g., dual-use in synthetic biology), and equity.

In doctoral contexts, these paradigms guide dissertation framing: choosing an engineering vs. discovery lens, integrating synthetic biology with biomaterials, or leveraging AI for tissue models. The field continues shifting toward more integrated, programmable, and patient-specific approaches, driven by technological convergence. For subdomain-specific paradigms (e.g., neuroengineering or biomaterials), deeper dives into specialized reviews are recommended." 

